{{Infobox language |name=Khalaj |nativename=Arghu |states=[[Iran]] |region=Parts of [[Kerman Province|Kerman]]; Parts of [[Fars Province]], and Northeast of [[Arak, Iran|Arak]] in [[Markazi Province]] of [[Iran]] |ethnicity=[[Khalaj people]] |speakers={{sigfig|42,100|2}} |date=2000 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Altaic |fam1=[[Turkic languages|Turkic]] |fam2=[[Common Turkic languages|Common Turkic]] |iso3=klj |glotto=turk1303 |glottorefname=Turkic Khalaj |notice=IPA }}
'''Khalaj''', also known as '''Arghu''', is classified as a divergent [[Turkic language]] spoken in western [[Iran]], despite having much Persian influence.
==ISO confusion== ''[[Ethnologue]]'' and [[ISO 639|ISO]] list an [[Iranian language]] "Khalaj" with the same population,<ref>{{e18|kjf|Khalaj (Iranian)}}</ref> but ''[[Glottolog]]'' states it does not exist.<ref>{{glottolog|khal1270|Khalaj (Iranian)}}</ref> The Khalaj speak their Turkic language and [[Persian language|Persian]], and the supposed Iranian language of the Khalaj is spurious.<ref>Hammarström (2015) Ethnologue 16/17/18th editions: a comprehensive review: online appendices</ref>
==Classification== While initially thought to be closely related to [[Azerbaijani language|Azerbaijani]], linguistic study, particularly that done by Gerhard Doerfer, led to the reclassification of Khalaj as a distinct non-[[Oghuz languages|Oghuz]] branch of Turkic language.{{sfn|Kıral|2012|p=89}} Evidence for this includes the preservation of the vowel length contrasts of [[Proto-Turkic]] (PT),{{sfn|Cheung|Aydemir|2015|p=80}} word-initial *''h'', and the lack of the sound change *''d'' → ''y'' characteristic of Oghuz languages.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}
The preservative character of Khalaj can be seen by comparing the same words across different Turkic varieties; for example, in Khalaj, the word for "foot" is ''hadaq'', while the cognate word in nearby Oghuz languages is ''ayaq'' (compare [[Turkish language|Turkish]] ''ayak''). Because of the preservation of these archaic features, some scholars have speculated that the Khalaj are the descendants of the Arghu Turks.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}} Some [[Turkish people|Turkish]] scholars{{who|date=August 2018}} consider Khalaj to be one of the "last examples" of [[Old Turkic]].<ref name="halaçça">{{Cite web |url=http://turkoloji.cu.edu.tr/ESKI%20TURK%20DILI/mehmet_olmez_halaclar_ve_halacca.pdf |title=Mehmet Ölmez, Halaçlar ve Halaçça, Türk Halkları ve Dilleri: 2, s. 15-22. |access-date=2016-12-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180818115100/http://turkoloji.cu.edu.tr/ESKI%20TURK%20DILI/mehmet_olmez_halaclar_ve_halacca.pdf |archive-date=2018-08-18 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref>
==Geographical distribution== Khalaj is spoken mainly in [[Markazi Province]] in [[Iran]]. Doerfer cites the number of speakers as approximately 17,000 in 1968; Ethnologue reports that the population of speakers grew to 42,107 by 2000.
===Dialects=== The main dialects of Khalaj are Northern and Southern. Within these dialect groupings, individual villages and groupings of speakers have distinct speech patterns.
==Phonology==
===Consonants=== {| class="wikitable" style="text-align: center;" |+ Consonant phonemes{{sfn|Щepбак|1997|p=472}} |- ! colspan=2| ![[Labial consonant|Labial]] ![[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]] ![[Postalveolar consonant|Postalveolar]] ![[Palatal consonant|Palatal]] ![[Velar consonant|Velar]] ![[Uvular consonant|Uvular]] ![[Glottal consonant|Glottal]] |- ! colspan=2| [[Nasal consonant|Nasal]] | {{IPA|m}} | {{IPA|n}} | | | {{IPA|ŋ}} | | |- ! rowspan=2| [[Stop consonant|Stop]] ! {{small|[[voicelessness|voiceless]]}} | {{IPA|p}} | {{IPA|t}} | | | {{IPA|k}} | {{IPA|q}} | |- ! {{small|[[voice (phonetics)|voiced]]}} | {{IPA|b}} | {{IPA|d}} | | | {{IPA|ɡ}} | {{IPA|ɢ}} | |- ! rowspan="2" |[[Affricate consonant|Affricate]] !{{small|[[voicelessness|voiceless]]}} | | |{{IPA|t͡ʃ}} | | | | |- !{{small|[[voice (phonetics)|voiced]]}} | | |{{IPA|d͡ʒ}} | | | | |- ! rowspan="2" | [[Fricative consonant|Fricative]] !{{small|[[voicelessness|voiceless]]}} |{{IPA|f}} |{{IPA|s}} |{{IPA|ʃ}} | |{{IPA|x}} | |{{IPA|h}} |- !{{small|[[voice (phonetics)|voiced]]}} |{{IPA|v}} |{{IPA|z}} |{{IPA|ʒ}} | |{{IPA|ɣ}} | | |- ! colspan="2" |[[Approximant consonant|Approximant]] | |{{IPA|l}} | |{{IPA|j}} | | | |- ! colspan="2" |[[Rhotic consonant|Rhotic]] | |{{IPA|r}} | | | | | |}
===Vowels=== {| class="wikitable" border="1" |+ Vowel phonemes{{sfn|Щepбак|1997|p=472}} |- align="center" cellpadding="4" ! rowspan=2 | ! colspan=2|[[Front vowel|Front]] ! rowspan=2|[[Central vowel|Central]] ! rowspan=2|[[Back vowel|Back]] |- align="center" !<small>unrounded</small> !<small>rounded</small> |- align="center" ! [[Close vowel|Close]] | i {{IPA|[i]}} ī {{IPA|[iː]}} | ü {{IPA|[y]}} üː{{IPA|[yː]}} | ï {{IPA|[ɨ]}} ïː{{IPA|[ɨː]}} | u {{IPA|[u]}} uː{{IPA|[uː]}} |- align="center" ! [[Mid vowel|Mid]] | e {{IPA|[e]}} eː {{IPA|[eː]}} | ö {{IPA|[ø]}} öː {{IPA|[øː]}} | |o {{IPA|[o]}} oː {{IPA|[oː]}} |- align="center" ! [[Open vowel|Open]] | ä {{IPA|[æ]}} äː{{IPA|[æː]}} | |a {{IPA|[a]}} aa {{IPA|[aː]}} | |}
Doerfer<ref>e.g. {{Harvcoltxt|Doerfer|1971}}, {{Harvcoltxt|Doerfer|Tezcan|1980}}</ref> claims that Khalaj retains three [[vowel length]]s postulated for Proto-Turkic: long (e.g. {{IPA|[q'''aː'''n]}} 'blood'), half-long (e.g. {{IPA|[b'''aˑ'''ʃ]}} 'head'), and short (e.g. {{IPA|[h'''a'''t]}} 'horse'). However, {{Harvcoltxt|Manaster Ramer|1995}} challenges both the interpretation that Khalaj features three vowel lengths and that Proto-Turkic had this three-way contrast. Some vowels of Proto-Turkic are realized as falling diphthongs, as in {{IPA|[quo̯l]}} ('arm').
==Grammar==
===Morphology===
====Nouns==== Nouns in Khalaj may receive a [[plural]] marker or [[Possession (linguistics)|possessive]] marker. [[Declension|Cases]] in Khalaj include [[Genitive case|genitive]], [[Accusative case|accusative]], [[Dative case|dative]], [[Locative case|locative]], [[Ablative case|ablative]], [[Instrumental case|instrumental]], and [[Equative case|equative]].
Forms of case suffixes change based on vowel harmony and the consonants they follow. Case endings also interact with possessive suffixes. A table of basic case endings is provided below:
{| class="wikitable" |- !Case!!Suffix |- |Nominative|| - |- |Dative||-A, -KA |- |Accusative||-I, -NI |- |Locative||-čA |- |Ablative||-dA |- |Instrumental||-lAn, -lA, -nA |- |Equative||-vāra |}
====Verbs==== Verbs in Khalaj are [[inflection|inflected]] for [[Grammatical voice|voice]], [[Grammatical tense|tense]], [[Grammatical aspect|aspect]], and [[negation]]. Verbs consist of long strings of [[morpheme]]s in the following array:
:'''Stem + Voice + Negation + Tense/Aspect + Agreement'''
===Syntax=== Khalaj employs [[subject–object–verb]] word order. [[Adjective]]s precede [[noun]]s.
==Vocabulary== The core of Khalaj vocabulary is Turkic, but many words have been borrowed from [[Persian language|Persian]]. Words from neighboring Turkic dialects, namely, [[Azerbaijani language|Azerbaijani]] have also made their way into Khalaj.
===Numbers=== Khalaj numbers are Turkic in form, but some speakers replace the forms for "80" and "90" with Persian terms:
*1 - {{IPA|[biː]}} *2 - {{IPA|[æk.ki]}} *3 - {{IPA|[yʃ]}} *4 - {{IPA|[tœœɾt]}} *5 - {{IPA|[bieʃ]}} *6 - {{IPA|[al.ta]}} *7 - {{IPA|[jæt.ti]}} *8 - {{IPA|[sæk.kiz]}} *9 - {{IPA|[toq.quz]}} *10 - {{IPA|[uon]}} *20 - {{IPA|[ji.iɾ.mi]}} *30 - {{IPA|[hot.tuz]}} *40 - {{IPA|[qiɾq]}} *50 - {{IPA|[æl.li]}} *60 - {{IPA|[alt.miʃ]}} *70 - {{IPA|[yæt.miʃ]}} *80 - {{IPA|[saj.san]}} (Turkic), {{IPA|[haʃ.tad]}} (Persian) *90 - {{IPA|[toqx.san]}} (Turkic), {{IPA|[na.vad]}} (Persian) *100 - {{IPA|[jyːz]}} *1000 - {{IPA|[min]}}, {{IPA|[miŋk]}}
==Examples== (Excerpt from {{Harvcoltxt|Dorfer|Tezcan|1994|pp=158–159}} {| border="0" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="1" |- ! style="background:#eee;"|Translation ! style="background:#eee;"|[[International Phonetic Alphabet|IPA]] ! style="background:#eee;"|In [[Latin alphabet]] |- e&771 |Once, Mullah Nasreddin had a son. |{{IPA|biː ki.niː mol.laː nas.ɾæd.diː.niːn oɣ.lu vaːɾ-aɾ.ti}} |Bî kinî mollâ nasrəddînîn oğlu vâr-arti. |- |He said, "Oh Father, I want a wife." |{{IPA|hay.dɨ ki "æj baː.ba, mæŋ ki.ʃi ʃæj.jo.ɾum"}} |Haüdı ki "Əy bâba, mən kişi şəyyorum." |- |He said, "My dear, we have a cow; take this cow and sell it. Come with the proceeds, we will buy you a wife!" |{{IPA|hay.dɨ ki "bɒː.ba bi.zym biː sɨ.ɣɨ.ɾɨ.myz vaːɾ, je.tib̥ bo sɨ.ɣɨ.ɾɨ saː.tɨ, naɣd ʃæj.i puˑ.lĩn, jæk biz sæ̃ ki.ʃi al.duq"}} |Haüdı ki "Bâba bizüm bî sığırımüz vâr, yetib̥ bo sığırı sâtı. Nağd şəyi pûlîn, yək biz sə̃ kişi alduq!" |}
